            -120.701466,42.092236,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Drews Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 4,517-acre irrigation reservoir about 20 miles west of Lakeview, Oregon. The reservoir contains a small population of redband trout, brown bullhead catfish, and crappie. Lake County maintains a boat ramp with dock and a day-use area with shaded picnic tables.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brown bullhead catfish<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.623918,42.12296,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Duncan Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5eg9KYWhY3lMYMJoAKSzPzWdDRsY55y1Iv5bwFlAZqEv8MOd58BdYexyIqAE_PTv0s_3-O4x0Qz60yxGPBDbM78IwIGFTJDqfAlJ_ZzmLXk-MvVbeVC1LdjmfoHU_ZTOYNJC0Y2J0XI02TJh_xmmtXEKHJpfeTcA" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 33-acre reservoir 5 miles southwest of Silver Lake, Oregon. The reservoir is stocked annually with fingerling, catchable, and trophy rainbow trout. There is an 8-unit campground with pit toilet and a boat ramp. Fishing is good using bait, lures, and files. Fly fishing is better in the morning because this reservoir can be windy in the afternoon.<br> <br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5eg9KYWhY3lMYMJoAKSzPzWdDRsY55y1Iv5bwFlAZqEv8MOd58BdYexyIqAE_PTv0s_3-O4x0Qz60yxGPBDbM78IwIGFTJDqfAlJ_ZzmLXk-MvVbeVC1LdjmfoHU_ZTOYNJC0Y2J0XI02TJh_xmmtXEKHJpfeTcA</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.943637,43.071114,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>East Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6zSqaJCPEkPYBvWGTWHTrlOsAqINtMaGZL2-TKmmgjwCALBRAWoDvCSo7JLGjejoi2j1pU97I7rOeVTKb7WpEr47QUTL0R7wjT43-IWnysK2-RFRgDHm6lEj7JjEccHXAcY596uj85aO-2cZ5W" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 1,050-acre lake located within the Deschutes National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/centraloregon) appr. 35 miles southwest of Bend. This popular recreation lake is situated in a setting of wooded shorelines, sandy beaches and brilliant blue-green water. The lake is one of two trout lakes nestled in the caldera of the Newberry National Volcanic Monument (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recarea/?recid=66159), the largest ice-age volcano in Oregon.<br><br>In addition to fishing for kokanee, rainbow trout and brown trout, people come to this lake to picnic and camp. East Lake shares this outstanding geologic area with Paulina Lake and both lakes are well known for their large brown trout. East Lake is known for producing brown trout over 10 pounds. Anglers also like to target rainbow trout. It is a popular fly angling destination<br> <br>East Lake is 6,381 feet above sea level, is approximately a mile in diameter, and the average depth is just over 67 feet.<br> <br>Motorized boats are allowed on this lake and can launch at any of three locations - Cinder Hill Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=38324&actid=29), Hot Springs Boating Site (http://www.fs.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsinternet/!ut/p/c4/04_SB8K8xLLM9MSSzPy8xBz9CP0os3gDfxMDT8MwRydLA1cj72BTJw8jAwjQL8h2VAQAzHJMsQ!!?ss=110601&ttype=recarea&recid=38378&actid=78&navtype=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&position=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&navid=110000000000000&pnavid=&cid=null&pname=Newberry+National+Volcanic+Monument+-+Deschutes+NF+-+Hot+Springs+Boating+Site) and East Lake Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=38346&actid=29). Supplies are available at the East Lake Resort and RV Park.<br> <br>Fish species: brown trout, rainbow trout, kokanee<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6zSqaJCPEkPYBvWGTWHTrlOsAqINtMaGZL2-TKmmgjwCALBRAWoDvCSo7JLGjejoi2j1pU97I7rOeVTKb7WpEr47QUTL0R7wjT43-IWnysK2-RFRgDHm6lEj7JjEccHXAcY596uj85aO-2cZ5W</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.196162,43.731468,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Elk Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v54egGDTP0hbeLEd-Ekq5x3wbvwJHBA-6AA9a_-mhhcN9J1jRCiczB-NPkQBik3b35Oyxcd6yetW1AChmBXgw8s6dkXsyAXFvLWHQsPKOpWW0MHkMegJje1ATXVw1WYsF6PZP0E6mcNHFTj6EV6" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 250-acre lake in Deschutes County located approximately 32 miles southwest of Bend, Oregon. This picturesque lake offers sweeping views of Central Oregon's Three Sisters mountains as well as Mt. Bachelor. With depths of 25 to 65 ft., Elk Lake supports populations of kokanee and brook trout and cutthroat trout.<br><br>Camping and boat ramps are located at Elk Lake Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsinternet/!ut/p/c5/04_SB8K8xLLM9MSSzPy8xBz9CP0os3gDfxMDT8MwRydLA1cj72BTSw8jAwgAykeaxcN4jhYG_h4eYX5hPgYwefy6w0H24dcPNgEHcDTQ9_PIz03VL8iNMMgycVQEAIzTHkw!/dl3/d3/L2dJQSEvUUt3QS9ZQnZ3LzZfME80MEkxVkFCOTBFMktTNUJIMjAwMDAwMDA!/?ss=110601&ttype=recarea&recid=38860&actid=29&navtype=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&position=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&navid=110130000000000&pnavid=110000000000000&cid=FSE_003705&pname=Central+Oregon+-+Elk+Lake+Campground), Point Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=38950&actid=29) and Little Fawn Boating Site.. A fourth boat ramp is available at Elk Lake Resort (http://www.elklakeresort.net/), on the west shore of the lake.<br><br>Fish species: brook trout, cutthroat trout, kokanee<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
