      <Placemark>
        <name>Fall River</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6UaHdCPbehMRTHvEekW2uVxQcHB0JNxoeX6EBY6trstMTltl1eVrD6WatuoHk0VbocE3OsOgxR9yt4A3lZPwLwS81zMd1dsYI3S-LPIfXry65AsificNgAKegYscYvLbItHqxIMT8GyVroNXABV0btcLZZEX2kVos" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>The Fall River is a 12-mile long tributary of the Deschutes River. An ODFW fish hatchery is situated next to the river near its source about 25 miles south of Bend, Oregon and is open from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m.<br><br>Some catchable trout raised at the hatchery are released into the river. The hatchery grounds are open to the public. Limited to fly angling only. <br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6UaHdCPbehMRTHvEekW2uVxQcHB0JNxoeX6EBY6trstMTltl1eVrD6WatuoHk0VbocE3OsOgxR9yt4A3lZPwLwS81zMd1dsYI3S-LPIfXry65AsificNgAKegYscYvLbItHqxIMT8GyVroNXABV0btcLZZEX2kVos</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.541748,43.636075,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Fish Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4u3ES3l808tdaS2egM5pgdsTCkSWYBsjM2vTWVbF_CfhOwDBScgiufO39N3n50ZN974ra_o-RZeZ_Xxvi78HCD89eUAksdsSl2JiC7ydTXqZwoPv0GcKXbpVhKQHEraCsksASY9yxyZsPySmNsIe_w0160H5ds-jWS" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 20-acre lake located in Oregon's high desert about 14 miles southeast of Frenchglen. The lake is in an aspen grove near the rim of Steens Mountain, at an elevation of 7,200 feet. Camping is available nearby at several BLM campgrounds.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4u3ES3l808tdaS2egM5pgdsTCkSWYBsjM2vTWVbF_CfhOwDBScgiufO39N3n50ZN974ra_o-RZeZ_Xxvi78HCD89eUAksdsSl2JiC7ydTXqZwoPv0GcKXbpVhKQHEraCsksASY9yxyZsPySmNsIe_w0160H5ds-jWS</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.645391,42.738692,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Fourmile Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v77wvsfjKOriuEWik1geRGjzWrkG_KzxgGa4f1Avz18gvRezTYIdGonU2LaqDKXdWasAw_CZg-g_AoeICXnHzWjgxvkC42i1CigVNKnFqem7ST4f__c98WUbj7Nke9sNO-SNq4HuHI0y_Pfc0cfslJPoA" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 740-acre lake located within the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) approximately 40 miles west of Klamath Falls, Oregon. The lake access is west of Lake of the Woods and requires driving down a dirt road for six miles. This lake is at an elevation of 5,800 feet, and the access road is usually open by the Fourth of July, although the lake is open to fishing year-round. Fourmile Lake is a deep, clear lake with a maximum depth of 175 feet. Water levels fluctuate widely as 15,000 acre feet of water is dedicated for irrigating the Rogue Valley.<br><br>Fourmile Lake is generally stocked with legal- to trophy-sized rainbow trout in late June through August. Lake trout reaching 10 pounds are also available. Kokanee are rare as lake trout have reduced their numbers but average 14 inches. Brook trout are common but difficult to catch. Lake trout, brook trout, and kokanee are all self-sustaining populations. Only rainbow trout are stocked in the lake. Look for caddisfly hatches in July and termite hatches in October. Mosquitoes can be quite bad in the summer.<br><br>Camping is available near the shoreline at Fourmile Lake Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/fremont-winema/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=59727&actid=29), which is located at the foot of Mt. McLaughlin. The campground offers picnic sites, accessible tent and trailer campsites, drinking water, restrooms and an unimproved boat ramp. The Sky Lakes Wilderness (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/fremont-winema/recreation/recarea/?recid=60187) encompasses most of Fourmile Lake. Several trails lead to high lakes that are stocked every other year with brook trout. The most productive high lake is Badger Lake, which is approximately one mile north of Fourmile Lake. Other lakes within hiking distance that have fish include Squaw, Woodpecker and Long lakes.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brook trout, kokanee, lake trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v77wvsfjKOriuEWik1geRGjzWrkG_KzxgGa4f1Avz18gvRezTYIdGonU2LaqDKXdWasAw_CZg-g_AoeICXnHzWjgxvkC42i1CigVNKnFqem7ST4f__c98WUbj7Nke9sNO-SNq4HuHI0y_Pfc0cfslJPoA</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -122.247534,42.454621,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Frog Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5wXP3-RMibZPZRF6JYuKykCgMySag7ijFGo_ujrWJSvN836ReEI4i6xwQbgl3hpvrLRHW_YdIg3gHPHMVxz7w9nWDrcZHj86ykPtKIOFTZiUAyq1OaV6qkxDjp2VheacfzShMAe8MmJT5SxjA3Vw" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is an 11-acre pond located just off Hwy 26 on the Mt. Hood National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/mthood) about 8 miles south of Government Camp, Ore. This lake is heavly stocked with both legal- and trophy-sized rainbow troutthroughout the summer. Camping is available on the north end of the lake at Frog Lake Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/mthood/recarea/?recid=53102).<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5wXP3-RMibZPZRF6JYuKykCgMySag7ijFGo_ujrWJSvN836ReEI4i6xwQbgl3hpvrLRHW_YdIg3gHPHMVxz7w9nWDrcZHj86ykPtKIOFTZiUAyq1OaV6qkxDjp2VheacfzShMAe8MmJT5SxjA3Vw</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.696587,45.216783,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Haystack Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6Fywf_CzYKJendMY_fQgppClZt15jdYYQgnNU1_x-DVW2oFvB-ZknmZSDlMEXdzFHI_pt5fO9TtE0s91Oyqc3IXjQUTwU1kZ9l4-xvYyV2lTs5zE1sjRx5zdtJgy8g5tiCh6u4na6RqAScznqei5gBKxF7Q-_ySg" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a large reservoir located in the Crooked River National Grassland (http://www.fs.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsinternet/!ut/p/c4/04_SB8K8xLLM9MSSzPy8xBz9CP0os3gDfxMDT8MwRydLA1cj72BTJw8jAwjQL8h2VAQAzHJMsQ!!/?ss=110601&navtype=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&navid=110130000000000&pnavid=110000000000000&recid=38274&groupid=null&ttype=recarea&pname=Deschutes) about 9 miles south of Madras, Ore. This is an irrigation reservoir, so water levels can vary substantially seasonally and daily.<br><br>Haystack Reservoir is open year-round supports a diverse fish population. Legal-sized rainbow trout are stocked in mid-April. Moderate numbers of large brown trout and kokanee are also present, as are several species of warmwater fish.<br><br>Boat ramps and camping areas are available on the east and west shores. <br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brown trout, kokanee, crappie, largemouth bass, brown bullhead<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6Fywf_CzYKJendMY_fQgppClZt15jdYYQgnNU1_x-DVW2oFvB-ZknmZSDlMEXdzFHI_pt5fO9TtE0s91Oyqc3IXjQUTwU1kZ9l4-xvYyV2lTs5zE1sjRx5zdtJgy8g5tiCh6u4na6RqAScznqei5gBKxF7Q-_ySg</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.142592,44.495113,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Heart Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7TTaaFNbibl8X9OfasVei5RmJjL-DWIAvKDQyZI4BOSVW8dy6JWdwA2eBKkWBiLeCHBasdCSZ2WYSy7pjHpIHc3Gt3_fnHsURbNFP7ayzUMpk8fF_shMvJX7aRFDgWHWGvmyQx2U1fAg1vMMiV7hM" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 19-acre lake located on the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) in a secluded forest setting at an elevation of 5,700 feet. Access is by Forest Road #3715, which is paved but narrow. Boats are allowed on this lake but are restricted to electric motors and subject to a 5 m.p.h. speed limit.<br> <br>Kokanee and rainbow trout are stocked in the lake. Kokanee fishing can be very good in the spring and early summer. Catch rates on rainbow is generally good throughout the summer. Fat head minnow occur in the lake so lures and flies that mimic this food can be effective. Illegally introduced brown bullherad catfish were recently found. There is no limit on catfish; keep as many as you want.<br> <br>This is a day-use only lake. An improved boat ramp, two picnic tables and primitive restrooms are available at the lake. Camping is available nearby at Lofton Reservoir Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/fremont-winema/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=59711&actid=29).<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brown bullhead<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7TTaaFNbibl8X9OfasVei5RmJjL-DWIAvKDQyZI4BOSVW8dy6JWdwA2eBKkWBiLeCHBasdCSZ2WYSy7pjHpIHc3Gt3_fnHsURbNFP7ayzUMpk8fF_shMvJX7aRFDgWHWGvmyQx2U1fAg1vMMiV7hM</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.838864,42.255262,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Holbrook Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4BXr0dk3_Jus5fp1zvszlKfOYgCQ3aoehnYFGpMegjeqB0u3QVg9O7JBzr_KIirE5bk8PVZ-APNMs3TeBENxJaDzdd8WC45PQpHhX25xoEvZTJukHNIaA25_CJK-AVEgx7AYafYCT9F0xEd-VbZCpDiP-geSLHGRTAJQ" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 40-acre lake located within a quiet forested area of the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema), approximately 37 miles northwest of Lakeview, Oregon. This reservoir is stocked annually with legal-sized and trophy rainbow trout. A boat ramp and a few primitive camping spots are available at this reservoir at Holbrook Reservoir Forest Camp (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/fremont-winema/recreation/fishing/recarea/?recid=59709&actid=42).<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4BXr0dk3_Jus5fp1zvszlKfOYgCQ3aoehnYFGpMegjeqB0u3QVg9O7JBzr_KIirE5bk8PVZ-APNMs3TeBENxJaDzdd8WC45PQpHhX25xoEvZTJukHNIaA25_CJK-AVEgx7AYafYCT9F0xEd-VbZCpDiP-geSLHGRTAJQ</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.853187,42.265575,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Horseshoe Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 14-acre lake located in the Olallie Lake Basin on the Mt. Hood National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/mthood). There are a few campsites available at Horseshoe Lake Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/mthood).<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.896025,43.923051,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Hosmer Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v61Q2CbcYe_RAf22sRRHiiHxfW_W5vonZtKyGeFUiJS8FfEV32NpUGw1LXUbn_uupsFMbUrCUH470TeAip09Sc2s47N9SCCzRO8jGJicQcOyb0u7mKrBOLdId0F6gPnj3lCM8mV7gJiRCejq7NTbZM" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 112-acre lake located about 37 miles southwest of Bend, Oregon. It is well known for its breathtaking views of Mt. Bachelor, South Sisters, and Broken Top, as well as Atlantic salmon, brook trout and rainbow trout.<br><br>Deep snow is typical during the winter, limiting road access to June through October. Boating is allowed but is restricted to electric motors but not when fishing. Angling is restricted to fly fishing, and float tubes are popular for due to limited backcasting space. Hosmer is a popular canoeing and paddleboarding destination.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brook trout, cutthroat trout, Atlantic salmon<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v61Q2CbcYe_RAf22sRRHiiHxfW_W5vonZtKyGeFUiJS8FfEV32NpUGw1LXUbn_uupsFMbUrCUH470TeAip09Sc2s47N9SCCzRO8jGJicQcOyb0u7mKrBOLdId0F6gPnj3lCM8mV7gJiRCejq7NTbZM</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.785593,43.963477,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Jefferson County Pond</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a small pond located in Madras, Oregon, just west of the fairgrounds. Fishermen will find a variety of fish at this pond, including rainbow trout, largemouth bass and crappie. This pond is open only to youth 17 and under and individuals with a disabled angler fishing license.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, bass, crappie<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.14006,44.620105,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Juniper Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4sHAlFp0oCCqOrgN-HIlUTqKIyqMT_qLvajg1oCPgUUW-l2iVL6YpTg8r6pE6ne8FBYXN_mOl9ONt045TT9FVbDkbOWZeNrIBddngp4DCdd7lKC265s7T93ZLOVc3DkFdeHxbq1-_UL-XKFOQJUF2nNg" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a natural lake that is surrounded by both BLM administered land and private land. The lake is stocked biannually with hatchery cutthroat trout. Much of the east shore is administered by the BLM while most he western shore is private land.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4sHAlFp0oCCqOrgN-HIlUTqKIyqMT_qLvajg1oCPgUUW-l2iVL6YpTg8r6pE6ne8FBYXN_mOl9ONt045TT9FVbDkbOWZeNrIBddngp4DCdd7lKC265s7T93ZLOVc3DkFdeHxbq1-_UL-XKFOQJUF2nNg</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.339233,42.916206,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Kingsley Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 60-acre lake located about 11 miles southwest of Hood River, Oregon. It is also known as Green Point Reservoir. There is a small campground located at the north end of the lake. Boats are allowed. Bank anglers can fish from a gently sloping dam at the north end of the lake as well as other locations.<br> <br>Anglers should focus efforts early in the year, as the reservoir level will drop rapidly as the season progresses. This receiver sometimes receives excess adult hatchery steelhead from Hood River, when available.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, excess steelhead (when available)<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/RR/central/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/reg_changes/index.asp)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.673906,45.641138,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Krumbo Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4D9haUtA_V5xwWBoZOI3FqQM82HDeVjD1G9-boJPuBXQnjWQ63051aJKQTyhK13tUqGy8JUQZDcO0pyWU3tNfnCKMsUHbarCVsTr7S2mlTOnXKcw_QsmNH1ZeMbmGnHLtHbAYDa2Z7wt1LwWDQCFrVeYKzSA" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 150-acre reservoir on lower Krumbo Creek in the Malheur Wildlife Refuge (http://www.fws.gov/malheur/) approximately 45 miles south of Burns, Oregon. This reservoir is stocked with catchable rainbow trout. Best fishing is in the spring and fall. There is a picnic area and accessible fishing dock on the soutwest end of the reservoir.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, bass<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4D9haUtA_V5xwWBoZOI3FqQM82HDeVjD1G9-boJPuBXQnjWQ63051aJKQTyhK13tUqGy8JUQZDcO0pyWU3tNfnCKMsUHbarCVsTr7S2mlTOnXKcw_QsmNH1ZeMbmGnHLtHbAYDa2Z7wt1LwWDQCFrVeYKzSA</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.807225,42.950996,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lake Billy Chinook</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7Uvzo2hrMLp7oSmbCaAFewqetLc_wqYLAYRE-cggM14Stem-MSJL1gAYx8rQFjN_5GM4nGpga-mUho_Ec4jdzvEaYp__Yoz4Ro_zttCdCbuc7HFcfKt_r9IXNeySvPYN0leyD0qV-xjyo4ht4pg8-_uybUPni6Uozm" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a large reservoir about 8 miles southwest of Madras, Oregon created by the impoundment of the Deschutes River behind Round Butte Dam.<br> <br>Lake Billy Chinook is one of Central Oregon's most popular recreational sites. The reservoir supports populations of kokanee, bull trout, and smallmouth and largemouth bass. In addition to fishing, swimming, water skiing and houseboat rentals are popular activities.<br> <br>A boat ramp and camping are available at Cove Palisades State Park (http://www.oregonstateparks.org/park_32.php). A boat ramp, boat moorage, restaurant, and boat and houseboat rentals are available at Cove Palisades Resort and Marina (http://www.covepalisadesresort.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=12&Itemid=20).<br> <br>Fish species: bull trout, redband trout, brown trout, kokanee, largemouth bass, smallmouth bass<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7Uvzo2hrMLp7oSmbCaAFewqetLc_wqYLAYRE-cggM14Stem-MSJL1gAYx8rQFjN_5GM4nGpga-mUho_Ec4jdzvEaYp__Yoz4Ro_zttCdCbuc7HFcfKt_r9IXNeySvPYN0leyD0qV-xjyo4ht4pg8-_uybUPni6Uozm</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.265802,44.563995,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lake of the Woods</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6G4CMvoCA2Oo6qzETgsLG0ZS3wYq-7VzljmdLjdA5Q89qkFc7_vCwWcnrviOOkjzZSlQRXoxqBerplLQS4_a4rx8x92pSG0SFzA-HkxNraLkUfB_1oxjeSX7tprxBdj10SRi5wcBUvIFWnYFRnVDD4i86bwe8D" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 1,146-acre lake located within the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) between Klamath Falls and Medford, Oregon. This lake is located at an elevation of 4,949 feet above sea level and supports a wide range of recreational activities, including fishing, swimming, water skiing, picnicking, hiking, mountain biking and wildlife viewing. Water quality is very good with depths ranging from an average of 27 to 55 feet. It supports a diverse population of fish.<br><br>Camping is available at Aspen Point Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/fremont-winema/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=59725&actid=29) on the northeast shore of the lake and at Sunset Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsinternet/!ut/p/c4/04_SB8K8xLLM9MSSzPy8xBz9CP0os3gDfxMDT8MwRydLA1cj72BTJw8jAwjQL8h2VAQAzHJMsQ!!/?ss=110602&ttype=recarea&recid=59731&actid=79&navtype=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&position=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&navid=110400000000000&pnavid=110000000000000&cid=null&pname=Fremont-Winema+National+Forest+-+Sunset+Campground+at+Lake+of+the+Woods) on the west side of the lake. Amenities include piped water, flush toilets, RV dump station, accessible restrooms, boat launch and pier. A day use fee of five dollars is required at all campgrounds and boat ramps. Lodging is also available at Lake of the Woods Lodge, which offers cabins, a nice restaurant, store and gas. For more information, visit the Lake of the Woods website (http://www.lakeofthewoodsresort.com).<br> <br>The most popular fishing is for hatchery rainbow trout in the spring by boat. The most effective method is to troll deep to catch hatchery rainbow trout.<br> <br>Largemouth bass fishing is popular with small tournaments occurring every year. Look for largemouth bass around fallen trees, the many docks that occur in the lake, and around emergent vegetation such as lily pads.<br> <br>Small yellow perch are the most abundant fish in the lake and can be exciting fishing for youth. Small spinners or bait work well for yellow perch. Ice fishing for these fish is popular.<br> <br>A good population of brown bullhead occurs in the lake. A worm or other stink bait fished on the bottom work well for brown bullhead. Look for areas of submergent vegetation. North of Aspen Point Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/fremont-winema/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=59725&actid=29) has abundant brown bullhead.<br> <br>Fishing at night is allowed for trout to target the nocturnal brown trout. Trophy brown trout occur in the lake and fishing on the east side of the lake is most productive for brown trout. Try using flourescent colored lures in late evening near the Boy Scout Camp.<br> <br>Hardy anglers can hike into the Mountain Lake Wilderness (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/fremont-winema/recreation/recarea/?recid=60185) and fish for brook trout and rainbow trout in Weston Lake, Como Lake Harriette, Paragon and Mystic. The Pacific Crest Trail (http://www.fs.usda.gov/pct/) is nearby.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brook trout, brown trout, kokanee, black crappie, brown bullhead, yellow perch largemouth bass, smallmouth bass, tui chub<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6G4CMvoCA2Oo6qzETgsLG0ZS3wYq-7VzljmdLjdA5Q89qkFc7_vCwWcnrviOOkjzZSlQRXoxqBerplLQS4_a4rx8x92pSG0SFzA-HkxNraLkUfB_1oxjeSX7tprxBdj10SRi5wcBUvIFWnYFRnVDD4i86bwe8D</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -122.210793,42.377865,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Laurance Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7gPv_G1S7N23Lw4kXsfUx4_LnLLVo3kWjpm4bXBh0Cb1Z8xfbKjoO1Wjf2_vzER5qEfWzPrx-yB79OY4wIuomYVCOKSnRyuv5pWqx49ch5mngUAXnXdNvHJ087_uq9e8wjp8GFm3vJ_xkytR46lJX-btDZUww" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 104-acre irrigation reservoir located on the Mt. Hood National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/mthood) about 23 miles southwest of Hood River, Oregon. Water levels fluctuate with irrigation draws so best to check ahead before heading out to this reservoir. There is a primitive campground and boat ramp at the south end of the reservoir, just off of Laurance Lake Rd.<br><br>This reservoir is open from late April through October and is stocked with catchable rainbow trout. It also supports a small population of bull trout. Only adipose fin-clipped trout may be retained.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, cutthroat trout, brown trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7gPv_G1S7N23Lw4kXsfUx4_LnLLVo3kWjpm4bXBh0Cb1Z8xfbKjoO1Wjf2_vzER5qEfWzPrx-yB79OY4wIuomYVCOKSnRyuv5pWqx49ch5mngUAXnXdNvHJ087_uq9e8wjp8GFm3vJ_xkytR46lJX-btDZUww</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.657383,45.459995,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lofton Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v68pffJZtH7EQ2dRHEj0gRIkHKpE7De_PlBClRHMUjLjtlYdpTviCDMPQr-pr1H3s6FgsxLAOHkNTJeNIx2an6fUmGIojaoBhTHva7yjc4LqZlFFyt3jU9TeR_mjL5azK4jPUFC-LLBX1Z7FiKqTjqzv6Pk_w" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 42-acre reservoir located in a forest setting at an elevation of 6,100 ft. within the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) approximately 39 miles northwest of Lakeview, Oregon. This reservoir is stocked annually with fingerlings, legal-sized and trophy rainbow trout. Fishing is generally best in the spring. <br>Look for brownrecreation signs on highway 140 directing people to “Lofton Recreation Area”. Itis about 9 miles from highway 140 to Lofton Reservoir. Picnic tables, primitive restrooms, campsites, and primitive restrooms are available on-site at the lake at Lofton Reservoir Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/fremont-winema/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=59711&actid=29).<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, tui chub<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v68pffJZtH7EQ2dRHEj0gRIkHKpE7De_PlBClRHMUjLjtlYdpTviCDMPQr-pr1H3s6FgsxLAOHkNTJeNIx2an6fUmGIojaoBhTHva7yjc4LqZlFFyt3jU9TeR_mjL5azK4jPUFC-LLBX1Z7FiKqTjqzv6Pk_w</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.81856,42.260882,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lost Lake - (Mt. Hood)</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 231-acre lake located on the north slope of Mt. Hood within the Mt. Hood National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/mthood) about 25 miles southwest of Hood River, Oregon. It can be reached from Lost Lake Road (Forest Rd. 13) This lake is open year-round and provides excellent fishing opportunity throught the summer. The picturesque lake also offers excellent boating, although the use of motors is prohibited. Access is generally from when the snow recedes in May through late fall.<br> <br>This lake is stocked with legal- and trophy-sized rainbow trout. It also supports small populations brown and brook trout as well as kokanee.<br> <br>Lost Lake Resort (http://lostlakeresort.org/lost/index.html) at the north end of the lake has a boat ramp, boat rentals. cabins and tent and RV sites. Camping is also available on the east side of the lake at Lost Lake Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/mthood/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=53228&actid=29).<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brown trout, kokanee<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.818799,45.496477,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lower Owyhee River</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Trout tailrace trout fishery located in Owyhee River downstream of the Owyhee Dam. Catch and release only for brown trout. Rainbow trout stocked in to the river usually in early June.<br> <br><br>Fish species: brown trout, rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -117.248797,43.652752,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Lucky Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5TQ60DjbCXq7_IVFYUe5fYDcU3lJX3wg4Hw2hCkhwof3Y73zSaIRyqJ46ZvkHY3bvlNZ4rC6Eeij-5W-mNpoq2Vf1-_UMtHz8KHph8Oea3ng7ou98qahehC8uoT5yW2h49kmvN6eK0RaMM3cUqHIsTFORH28Aq" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 6-acre reservoir located within the Bureau of Land Management's Lakeview, Oregon District (http://www.blm.gov/or/districts/lakeview/index.php). The reservoir is stocked with fingerling rainbow trout annually. The reservoir is muddy all year and anglers should target areas along the margin of the reservoir to catch fish. Access to the reservoir is through private property with an easement. Please leave gates how you find them.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5TQ60DjbCXq7_IVFYUe5fYDcU3lJX3wg4Hw2hCkhwof3Y73zSaIRyqJ46ZvkHY3bvlNZ4rC6Eeij-5W-mNpoq2Vf1-_UMtHz8KHph8Oea3ng7ou98qahehC8uoT5yW2h49kmvN6eK0RaMM3cUqHIsTFORH28Aq</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -119.641113,43.012681,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Malheur Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 1,200-acre irrigation reservoir located north of Hwy. 26 between John Day and Ontario, Ore. This reservoir can go dry but is stocked with catchable and fingerling trout during wet cycles, and fishing can be very good during these periods.<br><br>The reservoir is open year-round but fishing is best in spring and fall. There is a boat ramp on the north shore and bank fishing sports around the reservoir.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -117.682114,44.360433,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Malheur River near Riverside</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Malheur River near the old town of Riverside, Oregon is stocked with fingerling-sized rainbow trout in the spring. These trout help to maintain a tailrace trout fishery located from Warm Springs Dam downstream to Juntura. Access is from Juntura on US Hwy 20, approximately 19 miles south on Juntura-Riverside Road.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.157959,43.572432,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mann Lake </name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v57rOXCj4g6aiB4CiKirIM61qkPEN50BzohcR1zk5JfYktiHEWl2vTRThKY124rPSkRw6mc9DQ-ntMQ1C_OqpotaTpBIAIX9hVja7hNNPfjwMlrCwWZoC-d7uLI0rxfeZb3eh_Nr4Hr6j7FGU4JYwnWwg" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a natural 200-acre lake located approximately 89 miles southwest of Burns, Oregon. This lake is surrounded mostly by BLM-administered land with some private land along the southeast corner. This lake stocked biannually with hatchery cutthroat trout. It has a two-fish bag limit and a 16-inch minimum size.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v57rOXCj4g6aiB4CiKirIM61qkPEN50BzohcR1zk5JfYktiHEWl2vTRThKY124rPSkRw6mc9DQ-ntMQ1C_OqpotaTpBIAIX9hVja7hNNPfjwMlrCwWZoC-d7uLI0rxfeZb3eh_Nr4Hr6j7FGU4JYwnWwg</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.451843,42.773227,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Miller Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6ri6kB4RJNdV6o0EFkiDbTWE8oTmC-XccdpP3o3mp_EJ6bpH4b8ANBFoJpt2nR8iW33t9yOFzQttwPUAK0DLG9JQUEd9K5OQNkGau8RPYS19MG3N4aabyZzuZwM0SjkZbHP23vbwEjjW0HAcNXEDMP" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 600-acre lake located on the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) approximately 12 miles west of Hwy. 97 and Chemult, Oregon. This lake is stocked annually with rainbow trout but is better known as one of the best brown trout fisheries in Oregon. Brown trout are stocked at 6 inches. Some natural production occurs in the tributaries of the lake. Browns are generally caught by trolling in the deeper water or fishing along the shoreline in the evening. Brown trout fishing is best in November near Evening Creek or near the outlet at Miller Creek. Kokanee are also available but typically are less than eight inches in length and very rare in the catch.<br><br>Digit Point Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/fremont-winema/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=59715&actid=29) offers a full array of activities, including camping, boating, swimming, fishing and hiking. Amenities include piped water, flush toilets, RV dump station and swimming beach.<br> <br>Abundant populations of small brook trout and brown trout can be found in Miller Creek at the outlet of Miller Lake. This is a great option for youths if fishing is slow in Miller Lake. Bait is allowed. Mosquitoes are very bad in the summer.<br> <br>Miller Lake lamprey were reintroduced into Miller Lake in 2010. ODFW would appreciate any reports of lamprey on fish or circular wounds that might be attributed to lamprey paratism.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brown trout, kokanee, Miller Lake lamprey<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6ri6kB4RJNdV6o0EFkiDbTWE8oTmC-XccdpP3o3mp_EJ6bpH4b8ANBFoJpt2nR8iW33t9yOFzQttwPUAK0DLG9JQUEd9K5OQNkGau8RPYS19MG3N4aabyZzuZwM0SjkZbHP23vbwEjjW0HAcNXEDMP</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.966503,43.227061,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mill Flat Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4pprZqihZwVBEzmO0sTGg0RnsnW0Gk3I0MXFOIHa1u_Emwl4ME7-9y7ca1QXrqQM3Z-FWywfb_IF_ZaTQ_dtXOtzTkMBfh6XUhfQVLoSjgoUzB4sDDA0bqMzW8ASLriqkFG0NGhZxZJzg2K3O0Hl7bxJsY2hdGwgLZIg" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is 2-acre pond located on the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) about 15 miles northwest of Lakeview, Oregon. It can be accessed by the Cox Creek road with passenger vehicles. The reservoir is stocked annually with fingerling rainbow trout that have later been caught in lengths up to 13”. This is great reservoir for people learning to fly fish because there are no trees or bushes to snag on back casts. It does become weedy during the summer, but a small section of open water remains along the dam.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4pprZqihZwVBEzmO0sTGg0RnsnW0Gk3I0MXFOIHa1u_Emwl4ME7-9y7ca1QXrqQM3Z-FWywfb_IF_ZaTQ_dtXOtzTkMBfh6XUhfQVLoSjgoUzB4sDDA0bqMzW8ASLriqkFG0NGhZxZJzg2K3O0Hl7bxJsY2hdGwgLZIg</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.395908,42.416384,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Moon Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7ex43iWGEB_jAJw4Js_QGSAadYNyyjPeuhqCFwxuRGK66sykjt4KcVN5yGWuklE-QiFoEMN-ON-oXgy5RZmm03SG86fEN1KeOtud__PNjV7zy3PB7VozNPtqGan0VV_yzUvjqaQmGGUfGzOtEa0sftsnqH" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 619-acre irrigation reservoir located about 16 miles west of Hines, Oregon via U.S. Hwy 20, then about 12 miles south and west to the dam. The last several miles is a rough dirt road. The resevoir is managed for both warmwater fish and trout. Fingerling-sized rainbow trout are stocked in the spring.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7ex43iWGEB_jAJw4Js_QGSAadYNyyjPeuhqCFwxuRGK66sykjt4KcVN5yGWuklE-QiFoEMN-ON-oXgy5RZmm03SG86fEN1KeOtud__PNjV7zy3PB7VozNPtqGan0VV_yzUvjqaQmGGUfGzOtEa0sftsnqH</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -119.398041,43.407292,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mud Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v46tDtXW8suSRwwJKGRh2ZjIzfnrAj-1_stXeZ_95z-apecMTvzMJM97HphcH_JlUdCQ-4LvEANWbz0fmlTp2vVz8j8VdLEq5v8-oU7PsSB0zvfZFoC-u9AiUyd5nRl6wg2I3s5s1gZZoOKQIOfYHuD" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 168-acre irrigation reservoir located within the Bureau of Land Management's Lakeview, Oregon District (http://www.blm.gov/or/districts/lakeview/index.php). The reservoir is stocked with fingerling rainbow trout annually. Sampling in 2012 found rainbow trout up to 12”. This is a great location to base out of and explore the desert, Hart Mountain National Antelope Refuge (http://www.fws.gov/sheldonhartmtn/Hart/index.html), or a cast and blast weekend for quail or chucker.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br><br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v46tDtXW8suSRwwJKGRh2ZjIzfnrAj-1_stXeZ_95z-apecMTvzMJM97HphcH_JlUdCQ-4LvEANWbz0fmlTp2vVz8j8VdLEq5v8-oU7PsSB0zvfZFoC-u9AiUyd5nRl6wg2I3s5s1gZZoOKQIOfYHuD</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -119.715443,42.211991,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Murphy Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a small irrigation reservoir located in narrow steep sided draw north and east of Beulah Reservoir near Juntura, Ore.. Bank access is limited to the dam area. Road is a narrow rough two track off the Beualh- Becker Horse Camp road. Road access is limted in spring when soft. Stocked with fingerling rainbow trout in late spring. In years with low conditions this reservoir may not be stocked.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.091354,43.986331,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Ochoco Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7SCU7biK-0Jl48Amqb6OqEx-pNLv61Ak1d2TGt1RP9299Ek2Z0ViErMwenWcL9YFFK3k9Tj3Q5iyBAIX7YfRdC3DwpDPph44Sjt0EWfKOR47YzN-vfhQYdOzvaAvT5oJz6oI77n8FppyerS1X8NIfDXV6MYHU" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 1,100-acre reservoir located approximately 5 miles east of Prineville, Oregon on Hwy 26. This reservoir is open year-around and is stocked with sub-legal rainbow trout, which later reach sizes of 12-15 inches. There are also wild redband trout available from natural production in tributary streams. Black crappie fishing is excellent during the summer months.<br> <br>Boats are allowed on this reservoir and can launch from a ramp at Ochoco Lake Campground (http://www.ccprd.org/OchocoLake.php), which has 22 self-contained camping spaces available April 1 through spproximately October 31 each year, depending on weather. Facilities include picnic tables, fire pits, restrooms and fish cleaning station.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, black crappie, smallmouth bass, brown bullhead.<br> <br><br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7SCU7biK-0Jl48Amqb6OqEx-pNLv61Ak1d2TGt1RP9299Ek2Z0ViErMwenWcL9YFFK3k9Tj3Q5iyBAIX7YfRdC3DwpDPph44Sjt0EWfKOR47YzN-vfhQYdOzvaAvT5oJz6oI77n8FppyerS1X8NIfDXV6MYHU</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.574951,43.842451,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Odell Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v44tWv7PL-H_jAla1A86_ImKboJ8-7ceuXuqdAP3AzGEQ1_uHInfXIUSnKtNB7b58xWIkirMOvcwOwfHYjzhZKvRGHkuEPEKpPkM6CKKygF_C7D_TjqVTRbI_QpwMbXH03Wm-_inKTbeoST_dQ2dcQ" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 3,300-acre natural mountain lake located on the east side of Willamette Pass approximately 70 miles southeast of Eugene, Oregon just off Hwy 58.<br> <br>Fed by a numerous small creeks and springs, this lake supports good populations of kokanee, lake trout and redband trout.The lake also supports a small population of bull trout, which are protected and must be released unharmed.<br> <br>There are several improved boat ramps around the lake, and trolling with downriggers, leaded line and flashers are popular fishing techniques, as is casting from shore. Kokanee are abundant and average 11-13 inches while lake trout over 10 pounds are common.<br> <br>Camping is available at Princess Creek (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=39088&actid=29), Trapper Creek (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=39120&actid=29) and Sunset Cove (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=39112&actid=29) campgrounds, which are managed by the U.S. Forest Service. Overnight accomodations are available Shelter Cove Resort (http://www.sheltercoveresort.com/) and Odell Lake Lodge and Resort (http://odelllakeresort.com/), which offer cabin rentals, supplies, boats and tackle.<br> <br>Fish species: Kokanee, lake trout, redband trout, bull trout.<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v44tWv7PL-H_jAla1A86_ImKboJ8-7ceuXuqdAP3AzGEQ1_uHInfXIUSnKtNB7b58xWIkirMOvcwOwfHYjzhZKvRGHkuEPEKpPkM6CKKygF_C7D_TjqVTRbI_QpwMbXH03Wm-_inKTbeoST_dQ2dcQ</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -122.040424,43.581386,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Olallie Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is the largest of more than 200 lakes within the Olallie Lake Scenic Area. Located on the southern edge of the Mt. Hood National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/mthood) it is a popular summer recreational destination for people from Portland and Salem, Ore.<br><br>There are three campgrounds and a rustic cabin resort on this lake as well as a hiking trail that encircles the perimeter. Yurts, cabins, and boat rentals are available at Olallie Lake Resort (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/mthood/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=52978&actid=29). There is a boat ramp at Peninsula Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/mthood/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=52994&actid=29) on the southwest shore of the lake. Camping is also available at Olallie Meadows Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/mthood/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=52982&actid=29) and Paul Dennis Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/mthood/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=52990&actid=29). Olallie Lake is also a popular jumping off point for backpackers who want to fish the surrounding high lakes or access the Pacific Crest Trail (http://www.fs.usda.gov/pct/).<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.744995,44.851975,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Overton Pond</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5_DFXxYCiK1hRWMkdAC88HkFeynARNEAhjv3WoIUYDhHpU5no24q1E0jPIuEKjAi5AB4ry3QKiGi9ac59KPCVujhnJi1mOToD4ANjKnKNEeB6ISDJewWDSrxKXYMz5hk7xTu4HDS-a6SxqgvXzDkRc4wYDMw" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This small reservoir is located on the Fremont-Wnema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) about 20 miles northeast of Lakeview. This reservoir can be accessed using Forest Service Road #3615 then turning onto Forest Service Road #3624 when the pavement ends (about 15 miles off of Hwy 140). The reservoir is stocked with fingerling rainbow trout annually and they have been caught to 12”. Milfoil covers the pond from June to September but a hole can open when the wind blows from the right direction.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5_DFXxYCiK1hRWMkdAC88HkFeynARNEAhjv3WoIUYDhHpU5no24q1E0jPIuEKjAi5AB4ry3QKiGi9ac59KPCVujhnJi1mOToD4ANjKnKNEeB6ISDJewWDSrxKXYMz5hk7xTu4HDS-a6SxqgvXzDkRc4wYDMw</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.233291,42.374604,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Paiute Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5sHCZK7trTxKzhk2w2PNiNdBy1I5nVM36bOiP7xD1uK7YMRUv9tUo-kPs5QJLaRZXgr93pGFm0mX1Ind1eoRrJiDCTVFA0jHjuaFbPLtlQZo9OrrJ3FkoPKDUFgim5v0-6nsXcx4xY_LdiBY5H_PhKMc2Pwa64qQ" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is an irrigation reservoir located about 20 miles east of Adel, Oregon approximately one mile south of Hwy 140. The road to access the reservoir is located between milepost 49 and 50 and has a stop sign. Some years this reservoir is full while other years it is dry. The reservoir is stocked with rainbow trout and Lahontan cutthroat trout when there is water. The water is muddy and anglers should target the margins for better success. Ice fishing is available at this reservoir some years. Call the Bureau of Land Management's Lakeview Field Office (http://www.blm.gov/or/districts/lakeview/notesdirectory.php) to verify that water is in the reservoir. <br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, Lahontan cutthroat trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5sHCZK7trTxKzhk2w2PNiNdBy1I5nVM36bOiP7xD1uK7YMRUv9tUo-kPs5QJLaRZXgr93pGFm0mX1Ind1eoRrJiDCTVFA0jHjuaFbPLtlQZo9OrrJ3FkoPKDUFgim5v0-6nsXcx4xY_LdiBY5H_PhKMc2Pwa64qQ</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -119.558051,42.066706,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Paulina Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v68QiOfPLVBt17bhLgDbsc_2FCgeg69_JC-42CsyWgrjD6gIgEZWD-LSLzbmXyQmS5HI0YJloER5yzmG0cdDLz5tUZ8WAxkQLyXiEmpDsVG46Jkq7xOq1Z1nLSfko7mbQWD6295PK68A74zY_2ogcDKBQ" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 1,520-acre lake located within the Newberry Volcanic National Monument (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recarea/?recid=66159), about 25 miles south of Bend, Oregon. The lake is situated in the caldera of the Newberry volcano at an elevation of 6,350 ft. It has a maximum depth of 250 ft. and is open to motorized boats, which can launch from ramps at Little Crater Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=38400&actid=29) and Paulina Lake Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/camping-cabins/recarea/?recid=38442&actid=29). The Paulina Lake Lodge offers lodging, meals and supplies.<br> <br>Paulina provides great opportunity for brown trout, rainbow trout and kokanee. The state record brown trout was caught here.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brown trout, kokanee<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v68QiOfPLVBt17bhLgDbsc_2FCgeg69_JC-42CsyWgrjD6gIgEZWD-LSLzbmXyQmS5HI0YJloER5yzmG0cdDLz5tUZ8WAxkQLyXiEmpDsVG46Jkq7xOq1Z1nLSfko7mbQWD6295PK68A74zY_2ogcDKBQ</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.273313,43.712782,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Pine Hollow Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 240-acre irrigation reservoir located approximately 39 miles south of The Dalles, Oregon. The lake is surrounded by private homes but fishing access has been preserved through a 10-foot easment around the reservoir purchased by ODFW, although public bank fishing is limited to the area west of the south shore boat ramp and north and south of the east shore ramp.<br><br>There are two public boat ramps and a privately operated resort on the east shore. Fishing is allowed year-round, although the lake sometimes freezes over during the winter.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, largemouth bass, brown bullhead, bluegill<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.292185,45.242348,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Poison Creek Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5-eBTCma-MEr22U2nfCry90cPVEFMf8QFFSGxt4FtJKSo3D0hwCkqROfJmLD4nPRU9TXsqbjJ8IQAZ5nTn0iJiSDRdvFlCJqQQ2RMNkKoRBjXkiVXdK9YWCSVyokyQZoRWRT__1RNJf-T1tjZkGpz8w1O-6gJ94fRWhw" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a small BLM irrigation reservoir located about 38 miles north of Burns, Oregon within the Malheur National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/malheur). It is stocked in the spring with fingerling-sized rainbow trout.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
