            -120.722494,44.127675,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Prineville Youth Pond</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5hu7fGJu_2PB8vS-qZE8k283u1j4P6ROd4LS9nALsBHzl9ngmFCgg-BSEYcQzishCyQMxmvK81PHv8eoBXMB2rygqin5wIZp6-apVuvqPlQQCQ3j3RIZdoYSFEr9gfHyreJ9K9d9ertkByVn5RCl4vst-qGA" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>Prineville Youth Pond is a small pond located in Prineville, Oregon next to Crook County Christian School and across the street from Crook County Fairgrounds. This pond is stocked every spring and fall with catchable rainbow trout. Fishing is restricted to youths 17 and under. ODFW sometimes hosts family fishing events at this site.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, bass<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5hu7fGJu_2PB8vS-qZE8k283u1j4P6ROd4LS9nALsBHzl9ngmFCgg-BSEYcQzishCyQMxmvK81PHv8eoBXMB2rygqin5wIZp6-apVuvqPlQQCQ3j3RIZdoYSFEr9gfHyreJ9K9d9ertkByVn5RCl4vst-qGA</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.848912,44.29189,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Rock Creek Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4JqjfVC4er2kULk8uiAKN52DoADI38diVeQw9F1Itm64-NUsMtKK7GDmXfhcRUkOKRCGtE9JqkGN-JwtdH7YFrvNdrF1--xiggs6FdwlH439V_nY9g5GgNt_bFSkOBkmOhKtQTdKpCREMwbBwmxJgSYcQ6D314rJER4XMs" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 100-acre pond located within the Mt. Hood Forest approximately 43 miles southwest of The Dalles, Oregon. This reservoir is located in a scenic forested area and is subject to irrigation drawdowns in the summer. It is open to boats, and trolling can be an effective fishing tactic, although the lake is shallow and has plenty of bank access as well.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, largemouth bass, brown bullhead, bluegill<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4JqjfVC4er2kULk8uiAKN52DoADI38diVeQw9F1Itm64-NUsMtKK7GDmXfhcRUkOKRCGtE9JqkGN-JwtdH7YFrvNdrF1--xiggs6FdwlH439V_nY9g5GgNt_bFSkOBkmOhKtQTdKpCREMwbBwmxJgSYcQ6D314rJER4XMs</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.391115,45.22044,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sherlock Gulch Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7LijeqyHKnP4peKvqMOMmjYPTkor4eY7QQ_Uz3TySKBHCHTuAp34qx4NlsEN9n3hxoO8IMrapyr7QAoFCL3SBXU0k2BNlPQNKV82Q9_fcwN8XE6WmsPoRbOyl4g6uPs-OYMn0nxLgbU6Pr6nOFg13BIqJhtIuowANMbaBk7vh2LA" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 10-acre reservoir located within the Bureau of Land Management's Lakeview, Oregon District (http://www.blm.gov/or/districts/lakeview/index.php). The reservoir is stocked with fingerling rainbow trout annually and have been caught up to 12”. The reservoir is muddy all year and anglers should target areas along the margin of the reservoir to catch fish. A fun side trip would be to stop by the public sunstone collection area or one of the private companies that specialize in hunting for sunstones, Oregon’s state gem.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v7LijeqyHKnP4peKvqMOMmjYPTkor4eY7QQ_Uz3TySKBHCHTuAp34qx4NlsEN9n3hxoO8IMrapyr7QAoFCL3SBXU0k2BNlPQNKV82Q9_fcwN8XE6WmsPoRbOyl4g6uPs-OYMn0nxLgbU6Pr6nOFg13BIqJhtIuowANMbaBk7vh2LA</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -119.916415,42.743892,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Shevlin Pond</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Shevlin Pond is a half-acre pond located among aspen trees in beautiful Shevlin Park (http://www.bendparksandrec.org/.docs/pg/10071) four miles west of Bend. It is open year-round but often freezes in the winter. There is a casting dock and good bank access around the pond making this is a great place to teach inexperienced anglers how to fish.<br><br>Fishing here is restricted to juvenile anglers up to 17 years old. The daily limit bag is two trout with an 8-inch minimum length. The pond is stocked with rainbow trout from April to August, though fishing can be good through November.<br><br>Facilities include restrooms and a wheelchair accessible bridge and dock. Shevlin Park also has hiking and mountain biking trails with scenic picnic areas throughout the park. <br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.305542,44.672559,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sid Luce Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v65ZA6njkMRzsXYBTGDEg4z3bDdCCowSkHPJTlYVjiI10uG3gAvgmEKHfEvRlKhlGBQ4Y-YL_bJiN8EHKbiJYYXvHLt2jqAgfza7-6SWC3n5Xfg6ary4-o1nPb6-JKdPZ5iQoesvXzVChGmDS3iZh7m5Ltl9MJr0g4G" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 57-acre reservoir is located on Bureau of Land Management's Lakeview, Oregon District (http://www.blm.gov/or/districts/lakeview/index.php) approximately15 miles northwest of Plush, Oregon. The reservoir is stocked with fingerling rainbow trout annually. It has a maximum depth of 33’ and remains muddy all year. It is accessible mid-May to October with a high clearance vehicle.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v65ZA6njkMRzsXYBTGDEg4z3bDdCCowSkHPJTlYVjiI10uG3gAvgmEKHfEvRlKhlGBQ4Y-YL_bJiN8EHKbiJYYXvHLt2jqAgfza7-6SWC3n5Xfg6ary4-o1nPb6-JKdPZ5iQoesvXzVChGmDS3iZh7m5Ltl9MJr0g4G</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.089149,42.447829,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Simtustus Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a deep reservoir formed by impoundment of the Deschutes River behind Pelton Dam about 6 miles west of Madras.Ore.. It is bordered by the Warm Springs Indian Reservation on the western shoreline. The dam backs up about 7 miles of the river, which is accessible almost exclusively by boat. <br> <br>The reservoir is open to fishing from late April through October. It is stocked with legal-sized rainbow trout before opening weekend and through the summer. A tribal fishing permit is required in addition to a state fishing license.<br><br>There is a store, boat ramp and campground at Pelton Park. Boats are subject to a 10 m.p.h. speed limit on much of the reservoir, and boat landings on the west shore are prohibited, except at Indian Park.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brown trout, kokanee, largemouth bass, bull trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.253314,44.660106,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Slide Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4wV6z8CxEBcc4b83D6NoxDuoac59cmU0zoJcMn2qHGpl5VOrxlq4A6yJraiFZsA7JEgsr74Q4c5XJ7NOiNBNX6Bmhoyw6qcRpDRN0GrlurafNvuflST9_8k2aJUey7H3fmpoAIHmdXWmaCHr1MckGlB3Q" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a small lake located on the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) between Summer Lake and Paisley. Anglers can access the trail from the Government Harvey Pass road coming from Summer Lake or via the High Line road coming from Paisley. Anglers follow a ½ mile trail to the lake, but can be rewarded with rainbow trout 16” or larger. The fish are stocked annually with fingerling rainbow trout.<br><br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4wV6z8CxEBcc4b83D6NoxDuoac59cmU0zoJcMn2qHGpl5VOrxlq4A6yJraiFZsA7JEgsr74Q4c5XJ7NOiNBNX6Bmhoyw6qcRpDRN0GrlurafNvuflST9_8k2aJUey7H3fmpoAIHmdXWmaCHr1MckGlB3Q</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.729704,42.69283,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sparks Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6EUhakCClJ_EpIM4QUbovELbJAgVyLMLReKewqw9UigQ7qJiMSJMblv4TdB6dI6_FryViVatjVF-87uVHJRpUgV4KbTbQOkkAwKJx1y5CjRQg_bpIS3F8sq7Liy_NZ81t4i0-HFUdDlv0Ll3xel_h1" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 400-acre lake located about 25 miles west of Bend. It is a large, shallow, trout lake situated on the northwest edge of Mount Bachelor. It is the first of the high lakes visible from the Cascade Lakes Highway west of Bend and offers views of South Sister, Mount Bachelor, and Broken Top. Prior to 1997, Sparks Lake was a brook trout fishery and, although brookies are still available, the lake's featured species is now cutthroat trout. Restricted to fly angling only.<br><br>Motorized and non-motorized boats are allowed on this lake. However, fishing from a motorized boat is prohibited. Due to the spectacular sceneray and proximity to Bend, Sparks Lake is very popular with canoeists and kayakers..<br><br>Fish species: cutthroat trout, brook trout <br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6EUhakCClJ_EpIM4QUbovELbJAgVyLMLReKewqw9UigQ7qJiMSJMblv4TdB6dI6_FryViVatjVF-87uVHJRpUgV4KbTbQOkkAwKJx1y5CjRQg_bpIS3F8sq7Liy_NZ81t4i0-HFUdDlv0Ll3xel_h1</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.736755,44.013435,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Spaulding Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 20-acre reservoir located 30 miles southeast of Adel, Oregon within the Bureau of Land Management's Lakeview, Oregon District (http://www.blm.gov/or/districts/lakeview/index.php). A brown recreation sign is located on highway 140 at the turn-off for the reservoir. Another sign is located 11 miles down the dirt road. The reservoir is stocked with fingerling rainbow trout when water is present. Fish are currently about 10” and readily bite dark colored flies. Anglers should not attempt to drive to the reservoir if the road is muddy.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -119.369717,42.191041,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Suttle Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4u8Sn1zTKo5LeXkijksUlENPvSglxKqyHbCv3ntTqD4Id9qE7BDCCNhFj02eHvvIgmUgOcT8dORWl7_BfY18R4XrQ5Axaj0rXROJ63XIEcOIGQUlSDVAtVjhDnOA87sxesD2afJmpSk-3wDYMyrwvA" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 240-acre lake located within the Deschutes National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/centraloregon) about 14 miles northwest of Sisters, Oregon, just off Hwy 20.<br><br>In addition to fishing, this is a multi-use lake offers other recreational opportunities including, swimming, boating and water skiing. There are four boat ramps on the south shore of the lake, and U.S. Forest Service campgrounds on the northeast and southeast ends of the lake. The Lodge at Suttle Lake (http://thelodgeatsuttlelake.com/) offers lodging, cabin rentals, a restaurant and a marina with boat rentals and moorage.<br><br>Suttle Lake supports populations of kokanee, brown and small numbers of rainbow trout . Kokanee is the most popular fishery and takes place from May through August. Trophy size brown trout are also available<br><br>Fish species: Kokanee, brown trout, rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4u8Sn1zTKo5LeXkijksUlENPvSglxKqyHbCv3ntTqD4Id9qE7BDCCNhFj02eHvvIgmUgOcT8dORWl7_BfY18R4XrQ5Axaj0rXROJ63XIEcOIGQUlSDVAtVjhDnOA87sxesD2afJmpSk-3wDYMyrwvA</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.728918,44.425513,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Taylor Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 35-acre lake located adjacent to I-84 about a mile north of The Dalles, Oregon. This lake is open the entire year and stocked several times early in the year with legal- and trophy-sized rainbow trout. Most people fish from the bank along the north shore of the lake but float tubes and rubber rafts are also popular.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, largemouth bass, redear sunfish, crappie<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.206923,45.641198,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Thompson Valley Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v53DZXfdTzTE-9oB6oDhb698a_8Wg79NMLJLYeBtabn95zAgRIAxS3Ww1H4DheiQn0tB3e6lrAs9LnHxfVbQuCjYV4VE1p8rQifVzqCQ_wim5YWDw01ZqS4y23BJBNPsQvGPtxO7wTDAEMvT6fq7iDRqUv257cFig" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>Thisis a 2500-acre reservoir in a forested area of the Fremont-Winema NationalForest about 60 miles northeast of Klamath Falls, Oregon. This reservoir isopen year-around, and ice fishing is popular when snow allows access. Campingis available at two campgrounds (Thompson Reservoir and East Bay) and on thereservoir, and each has a boat ramp. The ramp at Thompson Valley Campground isgood for small boats, while the ramp at East Bay campground is better forlarger boats.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, largemouth bass, chub<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
