          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6v7JAFKQ2wSmgY32HHwkrq4z7syS9-clseAsFZvcrm2a_LozhQefjrqPSgJcJktnmQcua6GmMP53DJH6wqd8vX6ot8ShB0hEwAzbajzdB-prHeydyd6zZr195NXCQH66nVhZxRVsbuRWa7qlSwyZxLMbFtubI</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.624682,44.096092,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Twin Lake - North</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5o8EOyl6I2Uj0kYkIpfXvmRiTZho9zjoDEJaF0bIS-LpDXMdcYGuUiVSZfETwGNFcR6JIULzm77Av1EMubcY0Hl7igqprTJmtGKLxj_QDp-eMSmo-AlWpButA4scF6c9ZB9j5u9DzyYApdlaizBsvRjGaG" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 130-acre lake located within the Deschutes National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/centraloregon) about 45 miles southwest of Bend, Oregon. Open year round, it provides a fishery for 9 to 11-inch rainbow trout. It is a great family setting and provides good shelter from the wind. The lake offers good boat fishing, although use of motors is prohibited.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5o8EOyl6I2Uj0kYkIpfXvmRiTZho9zjoDEJaF0bIS-LpDXMdcYGuUiVSZfETwGNFcR6JIULzm77Av1EMubcY0Hl7igqprTJmtGKLxj_QDp-eMSmo-AlWpButA4scF6c9ZB9j5u9DzyYApdlaizBsvRjGaG</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.763792,43.731662,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Twin Lake - South</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6nKz-Oxav12lpTbHjO-bUXwnxGvFgI8uyXsIBjc879CXgd_bA2Bo8dj-cK8N8wteASRf-gKy8r_EqIvQGrEEQB1B7Q5E5quaPoeUGecqFYK-NJKBB5FLOiSUV3b_GYoyaL41VujozeTcCe_5srDOyy1Xn2sw" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 99-acre natural lake located within the Deschutes National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/centraloregon) about 60 miles southwest of Bend, Oregon off of the Cascade Lakes Highway. <br> <br>Consistent stocking of fingerlings and legal-size rainbow trout has resulted in an excellent fishery. Most anglers’ fish from boats and use bait. Depths of 15 to 30 feet are the best producers. Trolling slowly with a flasher and apiece of worm or egg or with a very small lure are productive methods throughout the season. Still fishing with eggs, worms, and a marshmallow or power bait far enough off the bottom to stay out of the weeds is also a popular method.<br> <br>South Twin Lake provides good shoreline access for both kids and adults. It provides a sheltered fishing venue when early season cold temperatures and wind become a problem on larger water bodies.<br><br>Only non-motorized boats are allowed on this lake<br><br>Camping is available at South Twin Lake Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/recarea/?recid=39002). The South Twin Resort offers lodging, accommodations and supplies.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6nKz-Oxav12lpTbHjO-bUXwnxGvFgI8uyXsIBjc879CXgd_bA2Bo8dj-cK8N8wteASRf-gKy8r_EqIvQGrEEQB1B7Q5E5quaPoeUGecqFYK-NJKBB5FLOiSUV3b_GYoyaL41VujozeTcCe_5srDOyy1Xn2sw</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.772161,43.714806,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Vee Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5pupb3S890VADAAlnzPiaf-E72kfh26UnwTMYK9KekXk1XY2guwZmFels6RINCiZNHOOqigt7_xF40gLBRgb9l57XKYMxNhLu_ZImv1d5Kt4O7nyIZZ_XAZLy0h25pr93Mzsn9j9ddcwlYKto" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This 14-acre reservoir is located on the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) about 25 miles northeast of Lakeview. This reservoir can be accessed using NF Road #3615 then turning onto NF Road #3616 follow the signs to the Vee Lake trailhead. The reservoir is stocked with fingerling, catchable, and trophy rainbow trout annually and they have been caught to 14”. There are two campsites and a pit toilet and boat ramp for small boats or float tubes. Vegetation can be an issue for bank anglers during the summer. This is a great location to fish and view Hart Mountain National Antelope Refuge (http://www.fws.gov/sheldonhartmtn/Hart/index.html) or watch the stars during the summer. Access is limited to snowmobiles during the winter.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5pupb3S890VADAAlnzPiaf-E72kfh26UnwTMYK9KekXk1XY2guwZmFels6RINCiZNHOOqigt7_xF40gLBRgb9l57XKYMxNhLu_ZImv1d5Kt4O7nyIZZ_XAZLy0h25pr93Mzsn9j9ddcwlYKto</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.161848,42.42169,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Walton Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6sUQ1vFE-HLYB6uCepM84FcyzhggOkHPgUKKc9B-vb5cIwA373edN9WCKViSu6Zld00iTkBVaLkBEv7Tw1UrF1dk4kxzlO32SPULKB1OwJ6lDa31XQpUPRgfWtAo6hS3nzmQgGEriRDRQte7kyO01f" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 19-acre lake located on within the Ochoco National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/centraloregon) approxiamtely 31 miles northeast of Prineville. This lake is open the entire year and is stocked prior to Memorial Day weekend and throughout the summer, with holdover trout reaching 16-18 inches. Snow limits access during the winter months.Boats are allowed but are restricted to electric motors. Camping is available at Walton Lake Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/centraloregon/recreation/recarea/?recid=38766), which has a boat ramp, picnic tables, vault toilets and drinking water. <br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6sUQ1vFE-HLYB6uCepM84FcyzhggOkHPgUKKc9B-vb5cIwA373edN9WCKViSu6Zld00iTkBVaLkBEv7Tw1UrF1dk4kxzlO32SPULKB1OwJ6lDa31XQpUPRgfWtAo6hS3nzmQgGEriRDRQte7kyO01f</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.336943,44.433075,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Warner Lakes</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4FnAh3gnT88oaK6ZKreHSuYLz76rx6coP_tYlj8o3CyVEhjZEsbkAjZGmxx5_dX4NQg2GzaFtqteeHbjAyuZHCSfCvqpSx4lo5s16owjTEWkc7bFZcTMG07nine7tVsiICMpdNXtbO5bn_hIfbzksZhmfcmw" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a chain of lakes aligned from north to south throughout the Warner Basin of southeast Oregon. These lakes are located near the small towns of Adel, Oregon and Plush, Oregon. Crump and Hart Lakes usually have water, but many of the lakes to the north become dry for multiple years. These lakes have crappie and brown bullhead with the occasional redband trout. These lakes produce state record crappie when water persists for a few years. A campground with pit toilets is available at the ‘CCC camp’ on Hart Mountain National Antelope Refuge (http://www.fws.gov/sheldonhartmtn/Hart/index.html).<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/southeast-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4FnAh3gnT88oaK6ZKreHSuYLz76rx6coP_tYlj8o3CyVEhjZEsbkAjZGmxx5_dX4NQg2GzaFtqteeHbjAyuZHCSfCvqpSx4lo5s16owjTEWkc7bFZcTMG07nine7tVsiICMpdNXtbO5bn_hIfbzksZhmfcmw</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -119.841614,42.418388,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Warm Springs Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 4,200-acre irrigation reservoir located about 49 miles east of Burns, Oregon via U.S.Hwy 20, then 14 miles south on a dirt road to the boat ramp. This reservoir is managed primarily for warmwater fish, but a few fingerling-sized rainbow trout are stocked in the spring.<br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout, warmwater fish<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report & regulation updates (http://myodfw.com/recreation-report/fishing-report/central-zone/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.eregulations.com/oregon/fishing/)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.24173,43.602522,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Wickiup Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6edpEq4iXupqAjAqMon9P-dlzi1E59pVRliJ69n7SdmgNUFVI8EKYQH0VaxC7rHbJ4rFQ8f0lZs9pxRr-S_xaGzAvARQR0t578ymMLTOWojjcjuZ_P4K9Swqp3qw5Dm2SshIwEOz1-fWKMtePHH5qNb_CCaJfToz2A" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 11,200-acre reservoir within the Deschutes National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/centraloregon) created by the impoundment of the upper Deschutes River behind Wickiup Dam, approximately 40 miles southwest of Bend. This is one of Oregon's largest and most productive fisheries, offering self-sustaining populations of kokanee, brown trout, and rainbow trout. Both kokanee (up to 20 inches) and brown trout (up to 15 pounds) grow quite large here.<br> <br>This is primarily a boat fishery, although casting from shore is also popular. Depths range from 20 to 65 feet. Good boat ramps are available at Gull Point (http://www.fs.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsinternet/!ut/p/c5/04_SB8K8xLLM9MSSzPy8xBz9CP0os3gDfxMDT8MwRydLA1cj72BTSw8jAwgAykeaxcN4jhYG_h4eYX5hPgYwefy6w0H24dcPNgEHcDTQ9_PIz03VL8iNMMgycVQEAIzTHkw!/dl3/d3/L2dJQSEvUUt3QS9ZQnZ3LzZfME80MEkxVkFCOTBFMktTNUJIMjAwMDAwMDA!/?ss=110601&ttype=recarea&recid=38874&actid=29&navtype=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&position=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&navid=110130000000000&pnavid=110000000000000&cid=FSE_003705&pname=Central+Oregon+-+Gull+Point+Campground) and North Wickiup campgrounds at the mouth of the Deschutes arm, at West South Twin Campground (http://www.fs.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsinternet/!ut/p/c4/04_SB8K8xLLM9MSSzPy8xBz9CP0os3gDfxMDT8MwRydLA1cj72BTJw8jAwjQL8h2VAQAzHJMsQ!!?ss=110601&ttype=recarea&recid=39030&actid=31&navtype=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&position=BROWSEBYSUBJECT&navid=110000000000000&pnavid=&cid=null&pname=Central+Oregon+-+West+South+Twin+Campground) on the lower Deschutes Arm, Reservoir Campground on the southwest shore, and Wickiup Butte Campground on the southeast shore.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout, brown trout, kokanee, whitefish, largemouth bass<br> <br><br>ODFW Recreation Report (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/RR/central/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/reg_changes/index.asp)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6edpEq4iXupqAjAqMon9P-dlzi1E59pVRliJ69n7SdmgNUFVI8EKYQH0VaxC7rHbJ4rFQ8f0lZs9pxRr-S_xaGzAvARQR0t578ymMLTOWojjcjuZ_P4K9Swqp3qw5Dm2SshIwEOz1-fWKMtePHH5qNb_CCaJfToz2A</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -121.755767,43.705282,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Withers Lake</name>
        <description><![CDATA[This is a 5-acre lake located on the Fremont-Winema National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/fremont-winema) between Summer Lake and Paisley. Anglers can access the trail from the Government Harvey Pass road coming from Summer Lake or via the High Line road coming from Paisley.  The lake is stocked with brown trout annually and has naturally produced brook trout.  Brown trout range from 8”-14” with a few larger fish.  This is a beautiful lake to float tube during the summer or fall.  There is a 100-yard walk from the parking area to the lake.  A pit toilet located at the parking area.<br> <br><br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/RR/southeast/)<br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br><br><br><br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/reg_changes/index.asp)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0F9D58</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -120.702946,42.682767,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Yellowjacket Reservoir</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4UCP0E1NDg_toEjZl96hGAZBA0tWyxB37uzUhN8brDLIhwexHS0ef1RvFnwGWVsopIGnNqgU6Iv3V30EJ7SojrbbEvzqQ1a0YMLsji4LMYwb25dXlRrlJEsKxJVRozVNhB5etTN1QTincUyTdtblwxBzrrx9-E7YtN" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is a 35-acre impoundment located about 39 miles northwest of Burns, Oregon within the Malheur National Forest (http://www.fs.usda.gov/malheur). This impoundment is stocked in the spring with both legal-sized and fingerling-sized rainbow trout.<br> <br>Fish species: rainbow trout<br> <br>ODFW Recreation Report (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/RR/southeast/)<br><br><br><br><br>Trout Stocking Schedule (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/trout_stocking_schedules/)<br>Fishing Regulations (http://www.dfw.state.or.us/resources/fishing/reg_changes/index.asp)]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-53</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4UCP0E1NDg_toEjZl96hGAZBA0tWyxB37uzUhN8brDLIhwexHS0ef1RvFnwGWVsopIGnNqgU6Iv3V30EJ7SojrbbEvzqQ1a0YMLsji4LMYwb25dXlRrlJEsKxJVRozVNhB5etTN1QTincUyTdtblwxBzrrx9-E7YtN</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
